# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tk-tkinter
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:tk-tkinter/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:tk-tkinter/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk provides many widgets commonly needed to develop desktop applications, such as button, menu, canvas, text, frame, label, etc.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk has been ported to run on most flavors of Linux, macOS, Unix, and Microsoft Windows.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Like Tcl, Tk 8.6 supports Unicode within the Basic Multilingual Plane, while Tk 9 supports the full Unicode range.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk was designed to be extended, and a wide range of extensions are available that offer new widgets or other capabilities.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Since Tcl/Tk 8, it offers "native look and feel" (for instance, menus and buttons are displayed in the manner of "native" software for any given platform).
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Highlights of version 8.5 include a new theming engine, originally called Tk Tile, but it is now generally referred to as "themed Tk", as well as improved font rendering.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Highlights of version 8.6 include PNG support and angled text.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk was developed by John Ousterhout as an extension for the Tcl scripting language.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk versioning was done separately from Tcl until version 8.0.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk was written originally for Unix/X11, and proved extremely popular with programmers in the 1990s by virtue of its being easier to learn and use than Motif and other X11 toolkits of the time.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk was also ported to Microsoft Windows and Macintosh platforms, starting with Tk 4.2 and improved with native look and feel in Tk 8.0 (released 1997).
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Interest in Tk waned significantly from the late 1990s and onward.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] The default look and feel on Unix still emulated Motif, despite the mainstream replacement of Motif by toolkits such as FLTK, Qt, and GTK.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Widgets that became commonly used in applications (e.g. trees, combo boxes, tabbed notebooks) were not available in the Tk core, but only via multiple, often competing add-ons.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk 8.5, released in late 2007, corrected some of these problems by adding missing widgets to the core, introducing a new theming engine and modernizing the look and feel on Unix.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] However, because some code changes were required to incorporate these advancements, many existing applications retain the older Motif-inspired feel that Tk had become known for.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Tk is a platform-independent GUI framework developed for Tcl.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] From a Tcl shell (tclsh), Tk may be invoked using the command `package require Tk`.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] The program wish (WIndowing SHell) provides a way to run a tclsh shell in a graphical window as well as providing Tk.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] A library written in one programming language may be used in another language if bindings are written; Tk is integrated with the Tcl language.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Various other languages have bindings for Tk, a partial list of which is on the Tk website.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Bindings exist for additional languages which might not be listed, including Ada (called TASH), Go (through tk9.0), Haskell (called HTk), Perl, Python (called Tkinter), R (through the standard package: tcltk), Ruby, Rexx, and Common Lisp.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] There are several ways to use Tk from Perl: the Tcl::Tk and Tkx Perl modules, both of which use Tcl as a bridge to access Tk, and Perl/Tk, which provides native Perl access to Tk structures.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] The Python binding uses Tcl as a bridge to Tk.
[src:tk-tkinter/tk-software] Basic widgets are embedded into `toplevel` widgets, which in turn are usually hosted by the operating system in floating windows that can be moved around on the screen.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] The name *Tkinter* comes from *Tk interface*.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] Tkinter was written by Steen Lumholt and Guido van Rossum, then later revised by Fredrik Lundh.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] Tkinter is free software released under a Python license.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] As with most other modern Tk bindings, Tkinter is implemented as a Python wrapper around a complete Tcl interpreter embedded in the Python interpreter.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] Tkinter calls are translated into Tcl commands, which are fed to this embedded interpreter, thus making it possible to mix Python and Tcl in a single application.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] The official Python release uses Tcl/Tk 8.6 (rather than the more up-to-date 9.0).
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] There are several popular GUI library alternatives available, such as Kivy, Pygame, Pyglet, PyGObject, PyQt, PySide, and wxPython.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] The generic term for any of the building blocks that make up an application in a graphical user interface.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] Tkinter provides three modules that allow pop-up dialogs to be displayed: tk.messagebox (confirmation, information, warning and error dialogs), tk.filedialog (single file, multiple file and directory selection dialogs) and tk.colorchooser (colour picker).
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] Python 2.7 and Python 3.1 incorporate the "themed Tk" ("ttk") functionality of Tk 8.5.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] This allows Tk widgets to be easily themed to look like the native desktop environment in which the application is running, thereby addressing a long-standing criticism of Tk (and hence of Tkinter).
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] Some widgets are exclusive to ttk, such as the combobox, progressbar, treeview, notebook, separator and sizegrip.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] In Tkinter, the Frame widget is the basic unit of organization for complex layouts.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] A frame is a rectangular area that can contain other widgets.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] When any widget is created, a parent–child relationship is created.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] For example, if you place a text label inside a frame, the frame is the parent of the label.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] For Python 2, the only difference is the word "tkinter" in the import command will be capitalized to "Tkinter".
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] Pack it into position so it becomes visible.
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] , define coordinates in the frame, or window).
[src:tk-tkinter/tkinter] These are often compressed, and the order can vary.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] In a graphical user interface (GUI), a **graphical widget** (also **graphical control element** or **control**) is an element of interaction, such as a button or a scroll bar.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Controls are software components that a computer user interacts with through direct manipulation to read or edit information about an application.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] User interface libraries such as Windows Presentation Foundation, Qt, GTK, and Cocoa, contain a collection of controls and the logic to render these.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Each widget facilitates a specific type of user-computer interaction, and appears as a visible part of the application's GUI as defined by the theme and rendered by the rendering engine.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] The theme makes all widgets adhere to a unified aesthetic design and creates a sense of overall cohesion.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Some widgets support interaction with the user, for example labels, buttons, and check boxes.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Others act as containers that group the widgets added to them, for example windows, panels, and tabs.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Structuring a user interface with widget toolkits allows developers to reuse code for similar tasks, and provides users with a common language for interaction, maintaining consistency throughout the whole information system.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Graphical user interface builders facilitate the authoring of GUIs in a WYSIWYG manner employing a user interface markup language.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] They automatically generate all the source code for a widget from general descriptions provided by the developer, usually through direct manipulation.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Around 1920, *widget* entered American English, as a generic term for any useful device, particularly a product manufactured for sale; a gadget.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] In 1988, the term *widget* is attested in the context of Project Athena and the X Window System.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] The same year, in the manual *X Toolkit Widgets - C Language X Interface* by Ralph R.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Finally, still in the same year, Ralph R.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Any widget displays an information arrangement changeable by the user, such as a window or a text box.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] The defining characteristic of a widget is to provide a single interaction point for the direct manipulation of a given kind of data.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] In other words, widgets are basic visual building blocks which, combined in an application, hold all the data processed by the application and the available interactions on this data.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] GUI widgets are graphical elements used to build the human-machine-interface of a program.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] GUI widgets are implemented like software components.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Widget toolkits and software frameworks, like e.g.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] GTK+ or Qt, contain them in software libraries so that programmers can use them to build GUIs for their programs.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] A family of common reusable widgets has evolved for holding general information based on the Palo Alto Research Center Inc. research for the Xerox Alto User Interface.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Various implementations of these generic widgets are often packaged together in widget toolkits, which programmers use to build graphical user interfaces (GUIs).
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Most operating systems include a set of ready-to-tailor widgets that a programmer can incorporate in an application, specifying how it is to behave.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Each type of widget generally is defined as a class by object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Therefore, many widgets are derived from class inheritance.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] In the context of an application, a widget may be *enabled* or *disabled* at a given point in time.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] An enabled widget has the capacity to respond to events, such as keystrokes or mouse actions.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] A widget that cannot respond to such events is considered disabled.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] The appearance of a widget typically differs depending on whether it is enabled or disabled; when disabled, a widget may be drawn in a lighter color ("**grayed out**") or be obscured visually in some way.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] On pop-up dialogues, buttons might appear greyed out shortly after appearance to prevent accidental clicking or inadvertent double-tapping.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] Widgets are sometimes qualified as *virtual* to distinguish them from their physical counterparts, e.g.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] *virtual* buttons that can be clicked with a pointer, vs. physical buttons that can be pressed with a finger (such as those on a computer mouse).
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] A related (but different) concept is the desktop widget, a small specialized GUI application that provides some visual information and/or easy access to frequently used functions such as clocks, calendars, news aggregators, calculators and desktop notes.
[src:tk-tkinter/widget-gui] These kinds of widgets are hosted by a widget engine.
